\begin_layout Section*
Method Intuition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The general idea is to use two sliding windows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a time series 
\begin_inset Formula $S=(a_{n},...,a_{m})$
\end_inset

, a window 
\begin_inset Formula $P=(a_{i},....,a_{j})$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $i\ge n$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $j<m$
\end_inset

 represents the past, and a second window 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=(a_{k},...,a_{l})$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $k>j$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $l\le m$
\end_inset

 represents the present.
 At each time step 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 models 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{P}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{Q}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 will be created/expanded.
 Each model 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 will be created using MGNG; the details of how this is to be achieved are
 yet to be defined.
 Then it will be checked how well 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{Q}$
\end_inset

 fits in 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{P}$
\end_inset

, by means of computing a containment-metric 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 At present an idea for 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{t}$
\end_inset

 would be to calculate how much of the n-dimensional volume generated by
 the vectors of 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{Q}$
\end_inset

 intersects the n-dimensional volume generated by the vectors of 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{P}$
\end_inset

.
 Exactly how to calculate these volumes, or if this is definitely the method
 to use, is yet to be defined.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An anomaly warning should then be raised, when a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

anomaly-level
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

 exceeds a certain threshold 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

.
 A possible way to define 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
A_{t} & =\alpha\times A_{t-1}+C_{t}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le\alpha<1$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 should be parametrizable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The reason for defining 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 this way is to take into account the historic anomaly levels.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{t}$
\end_inset

 exceeds 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 by itself, then a warning is raised, if the sum of the accumulated anomaly
 level plus the current containment-metric exceed 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 then also a warning is raised, but, since 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 decays over time, after a time with low enough 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{t}$
\end_inset

s, 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 should return to its mean historical value (hopefully below 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

